Data analysis with PRI - Pattern Recognition with Immune cells

Yen Hoang & Ines Hoppe

11/30/2021

Data description

The dataset used in this tutorial can be downloaded from Cytobank. Our study used 13 blood sample files that are part of the dataset. Each sample has 41 measured protein markers and other device parameters resulting in 59 parameters for each samples meta data in total. Compensation, elimination of doublets and dead cells was done in FlowJo, as well as gating on CD4+ T cells.For comparability of the re-analysis results with the original results we used a gating strategy similar to the strategy in Spitzer et. al., 2017. The full gating strategy is presented in the supplements (reference).

Example analysis with PRI - Pattern Recognition with Immune cells

We have selected two files to demonstrate how we create binplots using the PRI approach. If the functions are to be used for other marker combinations or data sets, only the input parameters have to be adjusted accordingly and carefully.

We operated on R version 3.6.1 running under Windows 10 (64-bit). Help and plot functions use R core functionalities. These functions are accumulated in YH_binplot_functions.R.

Install library

We use the library flowCore v1.52.1 to read the FCS-FIles. If this library is not yet installed, it can be done via BioConductor in the R terminal before running the remainder of code in this tutorial.

if (!requireNamespace("BiocManager", quietly = TRUE))
    install.packages("BiocManager")

BiocManager::install("flowCore")

Load library

When flowCore is installed, we load the library and create an R environment for the demonstration of PRI functionalities.

rm(list = ls())
fcs = new.env()
library(flowCore)
source("../code/YH_binplot_functions.R")

1 General Example for Usage of PRI

This first section in the tutorial demonstrates the general steps of data preparation and visualisation using the example of a single file and the creation of a binplot. We use the file CD4_TIN_BLD1_Untreated_Day3.fcs

1.1 Data Preparation

We read in the file using flowCore and map aliases of the markers we are interested in to the channel names to use them as column names in the data frame we create for the raw data. The data is then transformed with inverse hyperbolic sine (asinh). This is a common transformation method for flow cytometry data (Finak et. al., 2010).

path.folder <- "../data/"
file.untr <- "CD4_TIN_BLD1_Untreated_Day3.fcs"
data.untr <- read.FCS(file=file.path(path.folder,file.untr),which.lines=1)
keys.untr <- keyword(data.untr)
aliases <- unlist(keyword(data.untr, c("$P5S","$P10S","$P28S","$P29S","$P33S")))
channels <- unlist(keyword(data.untr,c("$P5N","$P10N","$P28N","$P29N","$P33N")))
map.untr <- data.frame(alias = aliases, channels = channels)

# load data
exprs.untr <- as.data.frame(exprs(read.FCS(file=file.path(path.folder,file.untr),
                                        channel_alias = map.untr, transformation=NULL)))
# rename column names for channels we are interested in
for ( i in 1:ncol(exprs.untr)) {
  colnames(exprs.untr)[i] = strsplit(colnames(exprs.untr)[i]," ")[[1]][1]
}
# transform data with asinh()
exprs.untr <- asinh(exprs.untr)

1.2 Data Visualization Using The Binplot

In a binplot, we present two markers X and Y in a bin-based approach on the x and y axis together with a color-coded third feature. The third feature can be used to display a variety of options, like the cell density or information about a third marker, referred to as marker Z.

To do so, the area of the markers X versus Y is categorized into bins of size 0.2 x 0.2. Each bin contains several cells. For these bins we calculate statistical measures that we plot in a color coded manner similar to a heatmap. Low values are represented by blues, median values by yellows and high values by shades of red.

The plot created with the code chunk below uses CD90 as X-parameter, CD44 as Y-parameter and CD27 as Z-parameter. As thrird feature, we calculated the mean fluorescense intensity of CD27+ cells (MFI+).

### INITIATING PARAMETERS
featX = "CD90"
featY = "CD44"
featZ1 = "CD27"
cutoffs.man = c(6,4,2)
binSize = 0.2

### PLOTTING PARAMETERS 
par(mfrow = c(1,1),
    cex.lab = 1.4, cex.axis = 1.4,
    pin = c(4,4),
    mgp = c(2.0, 0, 0))

### CALL PLOT FUNCTIONS
fcs$binplot_table(
  data = exprs.untr, 
  feat.X = featX, 
  feat.Y = featY, 
  feat.Z1 = featZ1, 
  calc = "MFI+",
  binsize = binSize,
  cutoffs = cutoffs.man,
  plot.range=c(0.05,12,0.05,12)
)

2 Use of PRI to Identify Differing Activation Patterns

The second section of this tutorial demonstrates how PRI can reveal differing activation patterns between mouse blood samples coming from a common cancer model being objective to effective and ineffective treatments.

2.1 Data Preparation

The files used in this demonstration represent blood cells taken on day three of the experiment. We here again use the file CD4_TIN_BLD1_Untreated_Day3.fcs is an untreated sample. After preprocession of the raw data file 44083 cells remain. We additionally use the file CD4_TIN_BLD2_B6Antibodies_Day3.fcs as an effectily treated example. It has 22679 cells after preprocession.

Since we already prepared and loaded the untreated, we only need to load and prepare the treated example at this point. This is done in the some way as it was done in 1.1 for the untreated file. The expression data is also transformed using the inverse hyperbolic sine (asinh).

####### UNTREATED SAMPLE - used for binplot with 3 parameters
file.b6ab <- "CD4_TIN_BLD2_B6Antibodies_Day3.fcs"
data.b6ab <- read.FCS(file=file.path(path.folder,file.b6ab),which.lines=1)
keys.b6ab <- keyword(data.b6ab)
aliases.b6ab <- unlist(keyword(data.b6ab,c("$P5S","$P10S","$P28S","$P29S","$P33S")))
channels.b6ab <- unlist(keyword(data.b6ab,c("$P5N","$P10N","$P28N","$P29N","$P33N")))
map.b6ab <- data.frame(alias = aliases.b6ab, channels = channels.b6ab)

# load data
exprs.b6ab <- as.data.frame(exprs(read.FCS(file=file.path(path.folder,file.b6ab),
                                         channel_alias = map.b6ab, transformation=NULL)))
# rename column names for channels we are interested in 
for ( i in 1:ncol(exprs.b6ab)) {
  colnames(exprs.b6ab)[i] = strsplit(colnames(exprs.b6ab)[i]," ")[[1]][1]
}
# transform data with asinh()
exprs.b6ab <- asinh(exprs.b6ab)

2.2 Binplots Visualizing MFI+ of CD27 for T-cells From Blood Samples

The range of parameter X (CD90) and parameter Y (CD44) on x and y axis, respectively, is categorized into bins of size 0.2 x 0.2. Here, we used the mean fluorescence intensity of parameter Z+ cells (MFI+) as third feature in the binplots. In that case, we call these binplots triplots as we display information for three different markers. Moreover, the bins are divided into four quadrants using thresholds for CD90 and CD44.

All parameters were included in the analysis and bins with less than 10 cells were excluded. This minimum count of cells was used to balance the impact of identifying comparatively rare subpopulations while retaining statistical power.

### INITIATING PARAMETERS
featX = "CD90"
featY = "CD44"
featZ1 = "CD27"
cutoffs.man = c(6,4,2)
binSize = 0.2

### PLOTTING PARAMETERS FOR TWO PLOTS
par(mfrow = c(1,2),
    cex.lab = 1.4, cex.axis = 1.4,
    mgp = c(2.0, 0, 0),
    mar = c(2.4,2,2.5,0),
    oma = c(1,1,1,1))

### CALL PLOT FUNCTIONS
fcs$binplot_table(
  data = exprs.untr, 
  feat.X = featX, 
  feat.Y = featY, 
  feat.Z1 = featZ1, 
  calc = "MFI+",
  binsize = binSize,
  cutoffs = cutoffs.man,
  plot.range=c(0.05,12,0.05,12)
)

fcs$binplot_table(
  data = exprs.b6ab, 
  feat.X = featX, 
  feat.Y = featY, 
  feat.Z1 = featZ1, 
  calc = "MFI+",
  binsize = binSize,
  cutoffs = cutoffs.man,
  plot.range=c(0.05,12,0.05,12)
)

2.3 Binplots For Cell Characterisation in Treated Blood Sample using T.bet and Foxp3

To further characterize the cell subpopulations in the treated example we additionally analyzed triplots using T.bet (left figure) and Foxp3 (right figure) respectively as Z-parameter.

### PLOTTING PARAMETERS FOR TWO PLOTS
par(mfrow = c(1,2),
    cex.lab = 1.4, cex.axis = 1.4,
    mgp = c(2.0, 0, 0),
    mar = c(2.4,2,2.5,0),
    oma = c(1,1,1,1))

### CALL PLOT FUNCTIONS
fcs$binplot_table(
  data = exprs.b6ab, 
  feat.X = featX, 
  feat.Y = featY, 
  feat.Z1 = "T.bet", 
  calc = "MFI+",
  binsize = binSize,
  cutoffs = c(6,4,0.4),
  plot.range=c(0.05,12,0.05,12)
)

fcs$binplot_table(
  data = exprs.b6ab, 
  feat.X = featX, 
  feat.Y = featY, 
  feat.Z1 = "Foxp3", 
  calc = "MFI+",
  binsize = binSize,
  cutoffs = c(6,4,0),
  plot.range=c(0.05,12,0.05,12)
)
